div.p:
See how the Supple slave, is come about now: how Arrantly the Rogue Beggs: Oh! for God and his Peoples sake, and for the City of Londens sake. (I am in earnest; I must laugh before I can write on.) Might not this fellow be laid hold of, upon the statute against sturdy Beggars, and Lash'd? He has absolutely turn'd a piece of one of the Rump-Ballads into Prose.


Nay my Lord; (cries the Brewers Clerk) good my Lord for the love of God;

Consider your self, Us; this poor Nation, and that Tyrant Abroad;

Don't leave us: but George gives him a Shurg, instead of a Nod.
